bib_record.title: Partial charge-changing cross sections for neutron- deficient isotopes from Ni-58 fragmentation.

free_txt: The SIS accelerator of GSI.
Three different setting of the
projectile-fragment separator FRS at GSI.
.A geometrical abrasion-ablation model.
-By authors. The partial charge-changing probabilities
are determined by integrating the number of counts in
the different charge-removal peaks and by normalization
them to the number of incoming secondary-beam
particles. The measurements without secondary target
showed that the interaction rate in the detector
windows, in the detector gas and in the air between the
two ionization chambers is small, less 1.5%.Compared to
the interaction probability which varies between 10%
for the lead target and 30% for the (ch2)N target, the
target-out correction is estimated to have only a minor
influence on the general trends of the partial charge-
changing cross sections. Therefore, this correction was
neglet in the following.
. Scintillation detectors SCI.
.Two ionization chamber MUSIC1 and MUSIC2.
The errors of the experimental data are mainly due
to statistical uncertainties. Systematic errors arise
from uncertainties concerning the target thickness
less 1% as well as from those interactions in the
detector materials which are not corrected for in the
target-out measurements.
The SIS accelerator of GSI.
Three different setting of the
projectile-fragment separator FRS at GSI.
The secondary beams were identified via a
Delta-E-TOF-Magnetic Rigidity measurement in the
second stage of the fragment separator.
Details of
experiments. Total charge-changing cross sections for
neutron-deficient isotopes from Ni-58 fragmentation
were measured.
The secondary projectiles have been produced by the
fragmentation of a primary Ni-58 beam at 650 MeV/
nucleon impinding on a beryllium target, 4 g/cm**2
thickness.
By means of a Delta-E-B(P)-TOF measurement, the
fragments have been identified and their
charge-changing probabilities in targets of
polyethylene, C, Al and Pb have been determined.
Between the two ionization chambers, a target ladder
with four different targets was installed.
The target thicknesses were 2.728 g/cm**2 for the
polyethylene target, 2.323 g/cm**2 for the carbon
target, 3.254 g/cm**2 for the aluminum target and 5.466
g/cm**2 for the lead target.  These thicknesses yield a
secondary-beam energy of about 440 MeV/nucleon at the
center of the targets.
.By CAJAD.
